13 Charybdis] the dangerous whirlpool between Italy and Sicily, per- sonified in ancient mythology as a female monster. In the de Orat. 111. 163, Cicero raises an objection against far-fetched similes of this kind deinde videndum est ne longe simile sit ductum. Syrtim patrimoni, scopulum libentius dixerim ,⁸ Charybdim bonorum, voraginem potius. Clodius is compared to Charybdis and Scylla in Har. Resp. 59.

14 me dius fidius] ‘so help me the god of faith’3 supply some such word as iuvet: the omission of a verb in adjurations is common, so we find di meliora (sc. dent), di illi mortuo (sc. mala dent) ; cp. mehercules. In the sorms edius fidius, ecastor, edepol the e is probably a prefixed interjection.
